< Text>
We used Executive Car Service to pick us up in Costa Mesa and take us to LAX.  We also used them when we returned.  I was very impressed by the cleanliness of both vehicles, and it was apparent that the drivers enjoyed what they did.

Our first driver Mark was right on time, and got us to LAX very comfortably and was very pleasant.

Our return driver was Mylene who was also very pleasant and professional.  She was also right there when we got our luggage, so there was not any waiting around for her to show up.  We had a great ride and conversation back to Costa Mesa, and I would definitely request Mylene again to be our driver, and wish we could give her more than 5 stars!

This was the first time we have used Executive Car Service, and will definitely use them again in the future.  I particularly like that you are able to pay at the time of your trip, and to tip as you wish, without any fees being added upfront.< /Text>

<Text>Use them if YOU WANT to MISS YOUR FLIGHT.

We received couple of reservation confirmation emails on May.14 from Executive Car Service (E.C.S.) for a R/T transportation between Malibu-LAX, starting on Jun.10. 12PM.

On Jun.8, I called the E.C.S. to confirm the reservation; we received a following confirmation email that the company designated a driver for the Jun.10 12pm pickup.

Our experience with other Car Service companies have been that the company made a phone call few hours before our trip followed by a confirmation call by their driver on their way to our house with an estimated approaching time, NOT this company.

Not hearing from them, at 11:50AM, I called the company, was informed that the designated driver's car was broken (without informing us); a substitute driver was on its way, about 40minutes away!
We rejected their service; tried to find a local Taxi, none available at the time, so we jumped in our car and rushed to the LAX; eventually found a parking lot with a free spot (these days, parking lots require a reservation).

Driving to LAX was very stressful because of the time strain; we would had missed our River Cruise boat if missed the flight, consequently a costly trip to reach the boat.  Thanks to the flight delay, we made it, 3 weeks parking at LAX was $385.

This is a very irresponsible company; they care less that they can cause the customer a financial or other type of harms.
AVOID THEM; they are not worth your time or your money.< /Text><Pictures>None<//Pictures><response>{'time': 1571720222643, 'text': 'Hi Allan, first and foremost, let me apologize for what happened. <user>101839682262193572073</user><user_name>Dude< /user_name><Time>1589906248112< /Time><Rate>4<//Rate>< Review>
In A Nutshell:

-Ono Hawaiian BBQ is a very nice Hawaiian restaurant located close to downtown San Jose off Monterey Highway.
-It's very clean inside & they've plexi-glassed the cash register area due to new restaurant requirement re:  COVID19.
-The menu is simple, not too many complicated choices.
-The Hawaiian BBQ Plate and the Teriyaki Chicken Plate are items I've ordered.
-If you check your mail, you should look for their coupons b/c you can save some money w/ their various "free" offerings.

Overall, the food is very tasty & you get a good amount of protein, very good prices!<//Review>

< text>
Ono is clean and spotless. They wipe down their tables and chairs. The food is way better than other Hawaiian BBQ spots in town. They always get my order right. They have a variety in menu selections such as their bomb fried shrimp... and they offer to sub out carbs for a fresh green salad. Btw, Their macaroni salad is better than other places. <resp>None< /resp><Rate>4<//Rate>< review>
One of the better Hawaiian BBQ places, Ono serves fresh and not greasy. I tried the seafood platter which includes fried fish fillet, fried jumbo shrimp and (oddly) chicken teriyaki. These platters are served with 2 scoops of rice and a scoop of macaroni salad. I always ask for the reverse, 2 scoops macaroni salad, and one scoop rice. The fish is thick and flakey with a crispy panko style crust, the 3 fried shrimp are large and NOT overcooked (thank goodness) and the chicken was tender and still juicy and flavorful. Maccoroni salad...yum.<//review>

<username>Russell Camara</username><Date>1563146237471<//Date><user_id>102315408130447490681<//user_id>< Resp>

<rating>1<//rating>< review>
I LOVE Hawaiian food. That said, this was a disappointment. Let's start with the good. The staff was friendly if a bit distracted. The place is clean. You get a good amount of meat for the money.

Now the rest. My wife ordered the kalua pork and BBQ chicken plate. I ordered the chicken katsu and mixed BBQ plate. The kalua pork was overly salty and tasted like it was salted after cooking. The BBQ chicken was just OK. The BBQ beef was greasy. The katsu was OK but dry. The katsu sauce was overly sweet. The cabbage under the meat was also greasy. We left halfway through eating. If it wasn't already served in to go containers, I would not have waited to take it home for my dogs. I won't be returning.< /review>

< Review>
Came in with my wife to do laundry and we usually spend about $25-$30 in laundry every two weeks. Well considering that this is a newer establishment we figured that the machines would be faster , quicker, and better. Well they are not. We used their big load washers that were $6.75 a load, they didn't wash the clothes very good so we redid the clothes in two of those twice! My wifes whites are not exactly white anymore. We saw other customers having to rewash their clothing twice as well. And the dryers... Well one quarter, 25 cents, only gives you 6 minutes of drying time and some dryers only give you 4 minutes. Their medium heat selection might as well be the no heat selection. No lie. Our budget of $25-$30 to do laundry turned into $60! They dont wash right and they dont dry at all. And no we didn't over stuff the washers.. In case anyone was wondering. And All brand laundry detergent is a good quality detergent so it wasnt the soap. Im going back to Yucaipa Coin Laundry on the circle of Yucaipa Blvd and 2nd St. Its not new but their machines are always serviced and wash good. And 50 cents gets my clothes dry. Todays economy, you got to save every little penny that you can. And I honestly do not feel like over paying for horrible service just to make sure that somebody else covers their bill to keep their business running.< /Review>

< Text>
We did the special Hamburger Month special with a WAGYU burger - EXCELLENT QUALITY AND COOKED to perfection for $10 and almost double if you had a soft drink and "extra" such as grilled onions.
Could not ask the source because although the Hotel attendant picks up the phone immediately, there is no way to talk to the kitchen.
We chose PICK-UP and it was a nightmare if you did not have APPLE PAY, which we did not and so ordered on the computer.  We ordered at 3 PM, first slot open; were told "around 4:17PM" and got the order at 4:40 after waiting at the curb.   The guy who brought the food out was super unfriendly.  The fries were cold and hard as soon as we tried them in the car.
Would not order food from here again but would definitely go in for dinner..</Text>

<GmapID>0x80c2beb0bb7b9b4d:0x8d30fe20ba2f239e< /GmapID><Review>So we were super excited to go to this beautiful place for Valentines Day. I made reservations a week before for 8:30pm. It was a $200 deposit to make the reservations and applies to your dinner. We got there and waited in line about 15 min to check in. Finally got to the front and we were told we had to wait another 45 min for our table to be ready either at the bar or stand around and wait. Mind you, there is another line for the bar which looks to be about another 30 min wait, and it's cold outside because it's only outdoor dining because of covid. 1 hour later I go back to the front to check on the table, they say it's going to be another 30 to 45 min wait. It's already 9:30pm so we wouldn't be getting a table til almost 10:30. We canceled the table and went to Denny's lol smh. They told me that they overbooked and it really got away from them somehow. They said people were only allowed to be at their table for about 75 min and staying longer, but they weren't doing anything to keep ppl within their time. So overall, I was highly disappointed with how things went for Valentines Day. The food was probably really good but I would know because it took way too long. I've never had a reservation at a restaurant and had to wait more than 15 min, if that. I would probably go on a regular day just to try the food but never again on a holiday.

*UPDATE*

Here's an update after what happened on Valentine's Day. I was contacted to allow them to accommodate me and my partner for another dinner at the date of my choice. We did set a date and went back for the on the house dinner and drinks and let me tell you, it was exactly what I thought it would be. The food was amazing, the drinks were great, and the customer service was outstanding. The manager even came over to check on us and apologized for the Valentine's Day dinner fiasco. He admitted that it was definitely a crazy night and I see that they did improve on how to handle those kinds of occasions better. The music and atmosphere was also great. The waiter, Niko, was amazing and very attentive and accommodating. They even brought us a surprise dessert that was delicious! Overall, I truly appreciate them making up for the last visit and would definitely go back for dinner and drinks. STK has become a favorite and can't wait to try other items on their menu. Definitely give them a try.< /Review>< Resp>

<text>We gave this spot a second chance because Larry (the owner) invited my party back after a bad valentines day. I've been to many of LA's higher class restaurants like Arthur J, Perch LA, 71 above and Mastros etc. Stk is definitely the spot to go for amazing steak and amazing non-steak options. < review>
Go to Mastro‚Äôs in Beverly Hills instead.

STK used to be awesome - been to several around the country. This location in the W Hotel in LA has great atmosphere.

The place was 3/4 empty at 8:30 on a Friday  - I should have just walked out.

We ordered the A5 Wagyu - $30 per ounce, 4 ounce minimum - one 4oz, one 6oz. They were both bad. Gristly and bland. I was shocked at how bad they were. Everything on the plate was at most ‚Äòwarm‚Äô at best. Borderline cold.

Ordered the truffle fries - warm. Bland.

Ordered the Jalape√±o Cheese Grits - bland, not hot.

All the food came out quickly, no idea why it wasn‚Äôt hot.

A manager came by to ask about the meal - I told him the steak wasn‚Äôt good - he said he‚Äôd pass along my feedback to the chef.

The general manager came by and he was very empathetic.

Nice people all around, friendly and quick service. But the food was just not that good.<//review>

< Review>
The food wasn't the greatest. I ordered chicken and my date ordered fish. The chicken was a bit dry to the point I could have cooked it at home better.

As far as presentation, my date had her fish handed to her on a mini pizza dish (e.g. a black wafer) with zero condiments. The presentation was pretty pathetic considering this was an "upscale" venue where dinner costs at least 100 dollars or more

I will say that the waitress was awesome though. She was thoughtful and did everything she could to serve us and cater to us. I would have given it a 1 star but due to her attentiveness, I am rating this venue a 3.</Review>

<text>Life is good when you can afford to come to a shi-shi fancy hollywood steakhouse like STK on a whim with some good friends, enjoy some choice cuts of meat on sizzling plates, and down it with some vino and chatter while admiring the pretty people coming in.

DineLA was happening, so some college buddies and I made a date for me to try out  STK. One of my steak-and-bacon buddies had been rating this place #2 steakhouse in LA, and I had to try it. In the end, I had to agree with him. #2 steak in LA.

THE SCENE
Walked in, and was immediately impressed by the entry. Long awning with waterfalls and stone walls leads you in on a red carpet. Yes, we sure are hollywood adjacent. The hostesses are all in black, all young and pretty, and they lead you to your table once everyone is there. The tables are in a big open area, so it definitely isn't like an old-school mobster-esque steakhouse with enclosed booths and dark decor. Here it was dark, but only enough to be chic. The walls were textured and well lit. It felt slightly too masculine for a romantic date, but then again it still was a steakhouse. It was perfect for a friend reunion.

THE MUSIC
Normally, i would never dedicate an entire review section to the music, but holy balls whatever the DJ there was spinning had be in the best mood ever. Mashups -- EDM with 80s classic ballads, old school rock and kid cudi, I mean the most crazy stuff, but it was SO GOOD. I kept asking my human-jukebox friend what each song was because I could not stop listening and talking about how great the music was. Definitely will be back for Happy Hour to enjoy the tunes, wine, and cheap bites!

THE FOOD
After seeing some mixed reviews, I was worried I might not like my steak. After all, steak and I go way back, and I've been spoiled to have eaten some fabulous steaks in my day. I'm personally a char and sizzling plate kinda gal, which makes me partial to a certain Beverly Hills M****** Steakhouse that just makes it perfection. The steaks at STK were very decent indeed. The taste was spot on -- not too light a flavoring. I had the filet mignon (not bone-in) and it was still very delicious. The cut was soft to the knife, and slightly warm inside. The plate didn't overcook the meat at all. I also tried the skirt steak and the bone-in ribeye. The ribeye was pretty good, but I am a filet girl. The char was not as strong as I would have liked it, but I will take a good flavoring over an over-char. This was a well-cooked and very tasty slab of cow.

The parmesan truffle fries are rectangular 2x4 esque cuts of potato perfectly fried. steamy on the inside and crunchy outside, with parmesan that gave a perfect flavor and just enough truffle oil to me amazing.

The corn pudding was sweet but good. Very smooth. I thought it was mashed potatoes when I first had it.

The vanilla panna cotta was pretty well executed as well -- very soft, and served with nicely complimenting flavors.

OVERALL
I loved my night here. The food was not the best, but it was pretty damn good. Memorable and very nice night out on the town in Hollywood. I wouldn't hesitate to come back and enjoy another meal here.

OTHER TIPS
Go during happy hour if the price tag is keeping you away
Try to find street parking (a little difficult) or bring $9 for valet
Dress code is striclty enforced - no flip flops or beach wear
Go during dineLA -- 3 courses (steak included) for $45 and $14 for 2 drinks add-ons. GREAT DEAL.</text><Pictures>None</Pictures>< response>
None</response>

<text>It was totally unbelievable. New, juicy and tender beef with a tasty sauce, the burger was great. The fries were thoroughly seasoned and crunchy.< /text><Pics>None</Pics><response>None</response><gmap_id>0x80c2c7ed421034a5:0xe83df53b3e8b5a64<//gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
< user>
116071657411799000319<//user>
<name>Santos Sanchez</name><time>1579044062756<//time><Rate>4</Rate>< Review>
Upstage Burger is an outdoor restaurant with a walk up window that allows you to order through a screen. The screen allows you to customize your order which is nice. The seating has views of Bunker Hill and the rest of Downtown. They do have someone to assist with you with ordering, especially big your not use to a screen. The burgers are fresh and the seasoned fries are  delicious and hot. They also carry the Impossible burger, which is a great tasting plant based vegan option. This is pricier than a Habit, but not as expensive as the Counter. Your looking at $$ for a burger, fries, and a drink here. A bit pricey but definitely  enjoyed the food. Try them out as this is the only burger place in the area.</Review>

<rate>2</rate>< Text>
Dropped off my car nearly 4 weeks ago for what I thought would be a quick visit. I brought in my check engine light codes, told them to give it a once over to see what needed to be done and signed the paperwork with a "Promised delivery" of 5pm that same day... Still don't have it back.

Timeline:
Monday January 25th, I drop off the car at my 8:30am appointment time, explain all I mentioned above, and they send me home in a lyft and tell me they'll call when they know more.

Since I hadn't heard anything after a few hours I called to get a status update around noon. They hadn't even started on my vehicle yet, and finally decided to tell me that the codes i brought in meant they needed to do a complete tear down of the engine.

I checked in daily to see if there were any updates, i was told on Friday the 29th that they thought it was my timing chain and they still needed to do a tear down.

Saturday the 30th, I was able to get a loaner through them, after needing to get a rental earlier in the week because they hadn't started on my car yet.

I followed up on Monday and was told that they had no information for me yet.

Tuesday, February 2nd I'm finally told that the tear down has begun. I check in a few times that week but don't get any information until the next Tuesday February 9th.

Feb 9th, i get a list of repairs and parts that will cost more than what the car is worth, at this point I'm already considering just abandoning it and buying a vehicle at another dealer just to get things over with.

A week and a half later brings us to today, February 18th where I'm still driving the loaner they got for me, which has been the only upside so far in their service, and still waiting to see how much more than the worth of my car I'm going to be charged when I'm frankly considering leaving it to be their problem if I don't get more information or even better, my car which right now feels like I'll be lucky to see before the end of the month, even though I've already been given two possible ETAs.

I understand that parts take time to ship and repairs can take a while, but the lack of communication up front has locked me into being in their shop's mercy for the last three and a half weeks, which if I had been told up front that I might be a month before I saw my car again, I would have gone somewhere else right from the start.

I've been told they might be able to swing some discounts or cut off some hours of labor, but at this point I don't know if I'll trust the totals I'm shown because it's been in their shop for so long and I have no way to contest or question whatever they decide to tell me they've done.

Now, if I get my car back and all is well I may come bump this rating up, but so far the two stars is only because my main point of contact has been patient with my nearly daily requests for information and the fact that I was given a loaner to use in the meantime.

I haven't decided yet, but I may never be using this shop or dealership again in the future. I try to give the benefit of the doubt and as much patience as I can manage, but this has honestly been ridiculous.

-A frustrated customer who just wants his car back and to not have to be homeless to pay for it.< /Text>

How convenient I do however remember them trying to sell me an extra extended warranty for my paint and this is where it becomes interesting. The extended warranty on the pain and corrosion would have covered me for an extra four years had I had bought it but in the circumstance that my paint started peeling I would still have to argue with the dealership that I bought the warranty from on whether or not the areas were in fact peeling. In my research I have found that the dealership that I have been working with is in fact been paid to have my vehicle painted and restored completely however they did not pay the auto body shop to do the work and my truck was not completely painted and returned to its original state. <rate>5</rate>< Review>
I couldn't be more impressed with the level of service I received from Sierra.

After going to a few other dealerships in the area, I was referred over to Sierra Chevrolet.

From the moment I walked-in I was treated with respect, and could tell that your team was genuinely interested in earning my business.

I initially worked with Gus, Rashad, and Edward, who took me on a couple of test drives and explained the features of the cars I was interested in.  They were very knowledgeable, and took their time to ensure I understood everything.

Then I worked with Rudy to go over purchase options on the car I selected.  Rudy took his time and explained my options, including the rebates for electric vehicles.  Even though the dealership was very busy, I did not feel rushed, and everyone took their time with me.

I was very impressed that Rudy and his team were not pushing me into getting the car.  In-fact, Rudy told me that if I was able to wait one day, he would be able to get me a better deal since he could speak to another department the next day.  Even though he could have "closed the deal" on the spot, he did what was best for me as the customer, and took additional steps to get me a more favorable deal.  Very impressed!

Rudy came through with his promise, and called me early the next day to tell me everything was approved.  He then set an appointment for me to come-by that day to meet with his partner, Corey, so that I could be in and out as soon as possible.

The process from there was seamless.  The car was cleaned, washed, and charged; ready to roll.  Corey was super friendly and helpful, and explained additional features on the car.  I sat down with Steve in the finance department, and he explained all of the finance details, and gave me lots of helpful additional information on my new electric car.  Steve continued the trend of not being pushy, and taking his time to ensure I understood everything I was signing.

The most impressive part came at the end of the purchase.  My wife needed to sign a form for our trade-in, but she was unable to make it down to the dealership for a few days.  Corey and Rudy arranged for Gus to drive to my house (more than 15 miles away) in rush hour, so that my wife could sign the form there.  Gus showed-up on-time, explained everything to my wife about what she was signing, asked us if we had any other questions, and was friendly throughout the entire process.  UNBELIEVABLE CUSTOMER SERVICE!

Anyways, super impressed across the board.  Thanks for helping me out.

Keep up the good work!</Review>

<text>1.0 star rating

7/10/2016

This dealer has something akin to a superiority complex. I recently brought my car in to have the airbag system diagnosed. I had just been rear ended and the car's airbag light had come on with the message "Service Airbag." After talking to some mechanics and doing some of my own research online, I came to the conclusion that, at a minimum, the system had to be reset. It could have sustained more damage as well, as the seat belts had locked up, but for sure I was not going to escape the $100+ it would cost to reset the system. OK. I accepted that. So I brought it in and the parts representative confirmed that resetting the system would cost me at least $100+. My dad and I dropped off the car and the next day we came back inquiring on the vehicle. We were given a statement of work in excess of $4000 with the explanation that everything comprising the airbag system, with the exception of the airbag itself, since it did not deploy, would have to be replaced. This included the computer modules, the sensors, the seat belts, and all this other stuff. I then told the manager at the dealer that when the appraiser for the at fault party appraised the damage, he could only appraise what he could see from the outside. Since all of this was internal, this was not part of his appraisal. The appraiser's explicit instructions were to have whomever inspected the vehicle (that being the dealer here) contact the appraiser directly to discuss additional issues. The manager was absolutely adamant on NOT talking to the appraiser. "We do not deal with insurance," he said. "That is YOUR responsibility. YOU work it out with them." So let me get this straight. Most likely, the dealer is overcharging me with this statement of work because prior to showing up at the dealer, I had gotten some estimates that were significantly lower from some body shops regarding the airbag system. Yet I am giving the dealer a chance to make some money, but oh, he cannot be bothered with spending any of his precious time or energy dealing with the nitty gritty of contacting the insurance company who will actually be paying for this on my behalf. Could this be because he very well knows that he is overcharging significantly and that insurance will not agree to these exorbitant charges and so he figures that the best thing to do would be to go directly to me because I am an easy target for gouging? And then, of course, not only does he have to gouge me, he has to insult my dignity and my intelligence by instructing and educating me in a rather patronizing way that it is not the dealer's responsibility to deal with insurance bureaucracy but rather, the onus falls on the victim, who has already been traumatized enough with being in an accident. So I think I am beginning to construct in my mind what the mantra of this dealer is regarding its customers. 1. BS the customer, 2. Gouge the customer, 3. Insult the customer, and 4. Drive away the customer. OK. Point made. Since the dealer does not want my business, the dealer won't get it. Now or ever.<//text>< response>
None<//response>

I approach the third and he just stares at me. He's sitting in the chair... no actually the chair and he have become one. It was as if the chair absorbed his soul and was working him like a puppet. I had already locked eyes and begun the approach so I proceeded.

At this point "Rolando, the chair puppet" gives me a "whatdoyouwantwhydoyoucomeinhereandbotherme?" kind of a greeting. I said that I wanted to get my car repaired, and that the oxygen sensor is acting up. I said I have a warranty contract that I purchased at the Henry Curtis Ford in Petaluma when I bought the car used. I said while you have my car could you see if there is anything else that needs repairing while you're at it. He said "We don't do that. We will only tell you about something if we see it broken in the midst of fixing the problem. You know, like if a part is hanging or something." I look up at their services and fees board, point to the 'Vehicle Inspection N/C' line item. "What's that?" I ask. He says all chipper "That's our 28 point inspection (starts to trail off because he knows he's been caught)... uh we uh check the tire pressure and stuff"

I'm really feeling like his approach to his job is a "Prove your worth and then maybe I'll help you" style. Last I checked we were in a capitalistic society... you know, a 'I give you money and you help me' economy. I guess I stepped into the Club 54 repair place.

Then Rolando comments on my warranty, "I've never seen that warranty before".

"I bought it at the Henry Curtis Ford up in Petaluma"

"Never heard of it. We're GMC." turns to another guy (Jeff) "You heard of this?" Jeff saif no. "All I'm saying is if they pay by check we won't take it"

Now I'm a tad bit aggitated, and when I say a tad bit I mean like the Cuban government and the US government are a tad bit different. I say to Rolando "Aren't you supposed to try the sweets before the punishment?"

He takes my contract and leans over to Jeff with it. "You wanna help this guy? Evidently I'm not nice enough for him."

Wow. Gotta say that I was impressed by the carefree abandon in which he approaches his job security. Rolando, oh giver of annoyance, harbinger of nay saying. I hope one day the chair will release you and you can enjoy life once again...

I'm posting this even though they still have my car. I hope he doesn't spit on the engine or snip my brake lines.<//text>

< Text>
Staff and facilities are fine but BEWARE! After 6 months they're raising my rate almost 40%. Make sure you factor this in to your decision. I thought I'd just be renting there a few months but should've planned for contingencies and negotiated a longer guaranteed term. Live and learn.

Also, get your own insurance. My tiny locker is $144/year through them. Again, something I would've thought more about if I knew I'd be more than a few months.</Text>

I was not looking forward to what I expected to be a long and tedious process to obtain a unit.  I was thinking I should have had my lunch first.  However, Letty Lozano made the process so pleasant. 2015 Innovative Results review

As another year comes to an end, it‚Äôs my honor to give my highest recommendation to the best place in Orange County improve yourself. Innovative Results Period.

But..I know, I know that is strong statement to make with hundreds of gyms and personal trainer, even therapists for that matter throughout the county, but let me say that I have experienced the ‚Äúretail‚Äù gyms and a few ‚Äúbox ‚Äì fits‚Äù.  Sorry cross fit are so over rated and trainer abused with most having little training themselves. It‚Äôs a get certified get clients, get paid, done kind of relationship.

Who? IR trainers are the most evolved in the industry ‚Äì with in house workshops from other experts and innovators, to continued education, personal achievements and overall experience. Be it your first time or your 100th they drive their system of health and fitness, including mindset, movement and recovery to get you motivated and inspired. They are truly are focused on one thing ‚Äì Improving YOU!

What? Gains can be achieved anywhere and by anyone, but what drives you, what gets you to that next level? In most cases it‚Äôs by making goals, be it weight loss, lean muscle, strength, speed etc., the goal may not always be accomplished but a failure it is not, you always have a gain. Knowledge, experience and with IR behind you ‚Äì the desire to make the next one your best one.

Why? Accountably and to give yourself the best opportunity to improve. Most people need someone in their corner keeping them focused not just that hour training but to look beyond and feel empowered to improve all aspects of your life and livelihood. Innovative Results earns my top praise not because they have helped me get stronger and leaner, but because they have helped me be a better man.

All this eclipse what you are capable of getting elsewhere...so with a New Year beginning Innovative Results is Orange County‚Äôs # 1 Fitness Playground that must be experienced.

They call me Mr. Consistent.
Shane Galitski

<date>1615237454210</date><Rating>5< /Rating>< review>
When your water heater goes out just before the weekend, the last thing you want to do is place calls for quotes and have the companies you are working with go radio silent through the weekend.

That‚Äôs exactly what happened to me, with the exception of one company, Sierra Pacific. Jeff, a design specialist with Sierra made a trip to our house the next day (Friday), and continued to work with me through the weekend, even though I could tell he was off. When he discovered that the tankless unit I wanted was not the brand they carry, he and his team agreed to purchase that unit anyway, making me a happier customer. Hunter, their Design Engineer, was out the next day to ensure that all the specs were known and I received a quote. They understood that we were without hot water and their actions made us feel we were a priority.

By early the next week, Kyle and Dylan, the Installation Specialists, were at the house working. They checked the boxes of what you would expect; a call 30 minutes out, on time, kept the workspace clean, good communication with an inquisitive home owner, and a check in before they left the property.

Kyle‚Äôs attention to detail was phenomenal, and the gas line work, the plumbing work, and the installation of the Tankless water heater work all look great and were done at a competitive price. Dylan walked me through the functions of the Tankless, what app to download, and its use. Extra kudos to Kyle, who came by the house the day after the installation because I had some questions.

I asked Sierra Pacific to bid on the project because they did such a great job on our HVAC replacement a few years ago. They exhibit the same level of customer service detail they did back then, and because they did not set me adrift over the weekend, and came in near other bids in the end, I am certainly happy I made the choice to go with them.<//review>

< review>
I contracted Sierra Pacific through Costco for a complete new HVAC system.  Salesman Jonji was clear, informative and polite.  He simply took information about our needs and expectations and then made recommendations without a strong arm sales approach.  A few days contracting Hunter came out to do a site visit.  He, too, was polite, informative and efficient.  Then a week later Brad and his crew came to install.  They got straight to work, each seemingly knowing exactly his role.  They intentionally made sure our heating was up and running before they left that first day .  The next day they essentially completed the install with the exception of a trim piece and minor exterior painting that Paul took care of a few days later.  Each of the individuals involved were professional, pleasant and seemed to be well trained (including the office staff on the phone).  They prepared themselves and our house for the work (to prevent damage) and always left it clean.  All involved showed up on time for each step.  The effects of the new Lennox system were immediately felt.  Much quieter and smoother operation.  The condenser unit outside is half as noisy as the prior unit.  Many of my neighbors have been replacing their units (all about the same age) and chose to go with a smaller family run company popular in our community.  I specifically chose to go with Sierra Pacific because I wanted a larger company that had the Costco affiliation (and associated reputation to uphold) and that had a better chance of still being in business 20+ years from now.  I also wanted a company that seems to train and retain their craftsmen instead of routinely hiring off the street.  In other words I wanted skilled, competent staff to do the install and whom I can count on to be there in the future should I have any problems.  Sierra Pacific seemed to fit the bill.  I know that even top-rated equipment, if not properly installed can cause a lot of problems.  I feel that Sierra Pacific knows their products and how to properly install them.  Our experience with them so far has been great.  I hope it continues through the years. Would not hesitate recommending them.</review>

< Text>
01/08/21  We are disappointed with the follow thru after the initial installation.  We contracted for a Merv 16 Healthy Climate filter and on the last day of install we were informed that no one in CA had that filter in stock.  Well here we are 2 months later and a trip to the attic shows that we still have the Merv 10 filter.  Called the office and informed them of the filter that we had and then gave them the part number of the one that  should have installed and magically they can install it next week.  My suggestion is that the person who is coordinating the installations take time to review all the items in the contract and verify they are in stock BEFORE scheduling a day with the home owner.  Also, in order to meet their 2 day installation deadline the crew didn't have time to put some of the insulation back to it's original location and they didn't have time to use a magnet on a stick to cleanup some of the screws and nails in the attic.  The garage and driveway areas were left as clean as when they arrived and I thanked the crew for that.

< Text>
I've been using Sierra Pacific each year since they installed my pool's solar heating in 2013. At the start of every swim season I have had to call them to repairs leaks in the solar collectors. The service techs they have sent out are professional and quickly diagnose the problem and repair it, as well as checking other components of the system for leaks. I would have given Sierra Pacific 5 stars for this review, but for each of this year's 2 service calls, they have quoted me $198 for the in-warranty repairs, instead of the $97 charge I have paid every year before this. After reminding them that this is a 105% increase over previous years, and this is an in-warranty repair and not a full service, they have agreed to charge the standard $97.</Text>

<Review>I wish the office had contacted me when the techs were on their way as promised (to make sure I was home and available)--but communication has been an issue in the past between the office, techs and customer. (Half a star deducted.)

But once Mike and David showed up, they were great! Mike checked the actuator on the solar set-up while David fearlessly climbed to the roof to check and restore a disrupted connection with the control box.

Turns out the 5-year-old actuator had a bad plastic O-ring. Once it cracked, it put a strain on the motor, which eventually burned out. Upon checking the price list, Mike found out the actuator replacement had been lowered from $695 to $465 (expensive for an O-ring, lol), but a big savings. And he added a discount on top of it if I had the repair done today rather than having to come back out in the spring, so Mike saved me over $200 which was sorely needed and greatly appreciated! (Half-star added back.)

(My main beef is with the actuator manufacturer, ComPool, for their measly, we-have-no-faith-in-our-product 3-year warranty. Every American car, truck and SUV comes with the same length, and vehicles are a lot more complex than a tiny actuator!! No stars for them.)

What made a big difference to me is that Mike wasn't a corporate robot or a rigid "here's our policy, screw you" type. He was genuine, personable, and sympathized with the customer--and THAT is something sorely lacking these days and is one of the reasons I have stayed with Sierra Pacific for this long. < Review>
I had service on the LG mini-Split Unit heating/AC in my shop. The service was excellent: On time, efficient, and effective. Andy and Kevin worked steadily and happily. My mini-split is more-or-less like new, after serving me for 8 years already.

Since the mini-split service, I have had a high end Lennox HVAC system in stalled by Sierra Pacific, using their program with Costco.
